on, settler colonialism, and militarism. Amahl Bishara looks to sites of political practice—journalism, historical commemorations, street demonstrations, social media, in prison, and on the road—to analyze how Palestinians create collectivities in these varied circumstances. She draws on firsthand research, personal interviews, and public media to examine how people shape and reshape meanings in circumstances of constraint. In considering these different environments for political expression and action, Bishara illuminates how expression is always grounded in place—and how a people can struggle together for liberation even when they cannot join together in protest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPalestinian ArabszIsraelxPolitics and government. 0aPalestinian ArabszWest BankxPolitics and government. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Middle Eastern Studies.2bisacsh  aPalestine.  acommemoration.  aembodiment.  amilitarism.  apolitical expression.  aprison.  aprotest.  apublic culture.  aresistance.  asettler colonialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363210340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632103423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632103/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles